    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.35c.7"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">7</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        2117 Cleveland Place 
                        St. Louis, Mo. 63110
                        October 16, 1971
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine><hi rend="caps">R. D.</hi> 7</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri 65201</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Coincidences never cease to amaze me. Last winter I read Dr. Eiseley's <hi rend="caps">INVISIBLE PYRAMID</hi> and came upon a beautiful verse, "Once in a cycle, the comet/ Doubles its lonesome track,/ Enriched with the tears of a thousand years/ Aeschylus wanders back." It kept haunting me for two reasons: first, its rhythm; second, the name Aeschylus. Why Aeschylus?</p>
                
                <p>I looked up your books at the library and grabbed <hi rend="caps">LONESOME TRAIL</hi>. But it wasn't in there. Then I took <hi rend="caps">COLLECTED POEMS</hi>. And waht a joy to come upon it in <hi rend="caps">THE POET'S TOWN</hi>, which, like <hi rend="caps">T. S.</hi> Elliot's work, refers to so many bits of knowledge that one has to do a great deal of reserach. But nothing in the poem nor in what I could study about the Greek dramatist nor in comet's names that I studied answered my question. All these months I have thought, the answer will hit me tomorrow; it's probalby right before my eyes.</p> 
                
                <p>Finally, I was wondering if your publisher would pass a letter on to you, or if I should write Dr. Eiseley care of his publisher, since his book was so recent. Then on October 5, I opened the Post Dispatch.</p>
                
                <p>I hate to give up on reserach or any sort of puzzle-figuring. But I do. If you would have time to write me a line or two as to the why of the name Aeschylus in the verse, I will be most grateful.</p> 
                
                <p>And what a waiting list at the library for <hi rend="caps">BLACK ELK SPEAKS</hi>!</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Nadine See</signed> 
                    <signed>(Miss) Nadine See</signed> 
                
                    <note>Enc. return envelope</note>
                </closer>
                
                <fw>2</fw> 
                
            </div1>
